questions.question:
Consider the regular grammar below:
S -> aS | a
A -> aS | bA

The Myhill-Nerode equivalence classes for the language generated by the grammar are

A. {w | n_a(w) is even} and {w | n_a(w) is odd}
B. {w | n_a(w) is even} and {w | n_a(w) is odd} and {w | w has a b}
C. {w | (a+b)* and n_a(w) != 0} and {eps | w = epsilon}
D. {w | w ends in a} and {w | w ends in b} and {epsilon}

steps.apply:
For L = a^+:
- Class of epsilon: for any z, epsilon*z = z is in L iff z in a^+. So epsilon ~ b ~ ba (any string not in a^+ and for which future is the same).
- Class of 'a': for any z, a*z = az is in L iff az in a^+, i.e. z in a*. Same as class of 'aa', 'aaa'...
So there are exactly 2 Myhill-Nerode classes:
  [epsilon] = {w | w has no a, or w is not in a^+}
  [a] = {w | w in a^+} = {a, aa, aaa, ...}
